.TH "HTMLImageElement.Image" "JS" "July 26, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLImageElement.Image \- HTMLImageElement: Image() constructor
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Image()\f[B]\f[R] constructor creates a new
\f[CR]HTMLImageElement\f[R] instance.
It is functionally equivalent to
\f[CR]document.createElement(\[aq]img\[aq])\f[R].
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This function should not be confused with the CSS
\f[CR]image()\f[R] function.
.RE
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
new Image()
new Image(width)
new Image(width, height)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]width\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
The width of the image (i.e., the value for the \f[CR]width\f[R]
attribute).
.TP
\f[B]height\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
The height of the image (i.e., the value for the \f[CR]height\f[R]
attribute).
.SH USAGE NOTE
The entire bitmap is loaded regardless of the sizes specified in the
constructor.
The size specified in the constructor is reflected through the
properties \f[CR]HTMLImageElement.width\f[R] and
\f[CR]HTMLImageElement.height\f[R] of the resulting instance.
The intrinsic width and height of the image in CSS pixels are reflected
through the properties \f[CR]HTMLImageElement.naturalWidth\f[R] and
\f[CR]HTMLImageElement.naturalHeight\f[R].
If no size is specified in the constructor both pairs of properties have
the same values.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myImage = \f[B]new\f[R] Image(100, 200);
myImage.src = \[dq]picture.jpg\[dq];
document.body.appendChild(myImage);
.EE
.PP
This would be the equivalent of defining the following HTML tag inside
the \f[CR]<body>\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]img\f[R] width=\[dq]100\[dq] height=\[dq]200\[dq] src=\[dq]picture.jpg\[dq] />
.EE
